    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-02-25T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-02-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="230"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d230">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/240</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Wilson</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-02-25">25 <hi rend="smallcaps"
                                >February</hi>, 1915</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: We have already discussed the
                    matter here referred to, and, as you know, I fully approve of taking advantage
                    of the opening to present to Japan very frankly our views on her “suggestions”
                    or “requests”. I think those views can be made very weighty and conclusive. We
                    shall not have uttered a more important state paper.</p>
                <p>Faithfully Yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>W. W.</signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>P. S. It is evident that things are being pressed at Peking. It would be wise
                        to let Tokyo have our views by cable, I think, if it can be managed without
                        the intervention of the Press.</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
